result.execSummary:
The defendant Victoria A Harbick was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Criminal Case Settlement

Cases 16CM160,16CM310,16CM311 called together at 9:10am [MA]
Defendant Victoria A Harbick in court with attorney Whitney Hagemann.  Brookellen Teuber appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
ADA Teuber verifies victim rights compliance.

  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; pleas of " GUILTY  " entered as to Case 16CM160, Count #2 and 16CM310, Count #1; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses: any remaining counts of Cases 16CM160 and 16CM310; and 16CM311 in its entirety.
Sentencing arguments given by Counsel

As to Case 16CM160, Count #2 and Case 16CM310, Count #1 , the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 18 months, with conditions:

--Continue to take medications as prescribed by physician
--Sign releases of information for any health care provider to allow DOC access to medical information
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, or counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--no possession of dangerous weapon
--complete Certified Batterers' Intervention programming, if directed by DOC
--no acts or threats of violence
--to pay statutory costs, to include domestic abuse surcharge
--not to loose current employment, unless have better job lined up 
--not to enter into any romantic relationship during her course of probation

As to Case 16CM160: Days credit for time already served:  6 days
As to Case 16CM310: Days credit for time already served:  1 day

The Court grants expungement upon successful completion of Probation 

The Court orders Ms. Harbick to provide a DNA sample today
